		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=803"><span id=Scholar>GiddyGonzalus</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br><img src=/shared/user_star_ico.gif height=9 width=9><br>155 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.09]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Here are my experiences with the two classes at mid levels (30-45):<br><br>1) Paladins can take damage. Rangers can't. I've grouped with Rangers of the same level and (like another poster mentioned) the Cleric is ALWAYS healing them. With my higher AC and greater HP, the critters just don't endanger me as often.<br><br>2) Paladins can heal better. All Pallies bitch about the fact that a 14 Level Cleric can heal as well as a 38 Level Paladin, but at least we heal better than Rangers 8P&nbsp;&nbsp;And let us not forget about Lay on Hands ....<br><br>3) Paladins can find groups. I have not met a Ranger yet who hasn't complained about the fact that they can NOT find groups. I never have problems finding groups as a Paladin. I've thought about this one for a long time, because when I have grouped with Rangers I have seen some great benefits to their class, so why aren't they wanted in groups? I've come to some interesting conclusions with this one: a) Rangers don't heal between battles, they instead rely on someone else to heal (ie. Clerics/Druids/Paladins) since they have better healing spells. This is RIDICULOUS! I heal between fights to save the mana of the Primary Healer for fights. Rangers SHOULD do the same, but I have only once found one who did. If you're not going to use your Mana, you should be playing a Warrior.  b) Rangers take damage too quickly and are "mana sinks".  c) Surprisingly, a large number of Rangers do not know the proper grouping stategies. I think this is because they spend so much time soloing, just like Wizards. Tactics change when you are in a group, and those tactics that worked great when you were soloing can get a group into trouble. Too few Rangers out there have experience with other classes to see how those classes change the dynamics of a group.<br><br>4) There are very FEW high level Rangers out there, but there are a number of high level Paladins. This, again, is for a variety of reasons: a) the grouping problem mentioned above. Groups ARE required for the higher levels (unless you're a Necro, Mage, or Wizzie).  b) the frustrations of playing a class that (IMHO) get's screwed worst of all by Verant. No class is as difficult to play as a Ranger.<br><br>All this being said, a well-played Ranger is a HUGE asset to any group, the problem is that there are not enough well-played Rangers out there. Other classes (Paladins included) can "get by" with a certain amount of bungling by the player, but Rangers require a greater finesse.</p><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>________<br><br>I've travelled this world and have seen many wondrous things. You are not one of them.</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >1 Replies</td></tr></table><table width="100%"><tr><td class=mhback>&nbsp;</td><td class=mhback >Thread Subject</a></td><td class=mhback>Started by</a></td><td class=mhback>Replies</a></td><td class=mhback>Last Post</a></td><td class=mhback>Rating</a></td></tr><tr class=mlr>
